egrep -c ‘(svm|vmx)’ /proc/cpuinfo

make sure it returns a number larger than zero.

then install KVM and supported packages.

sudo apt-get install qemu-kvm libvirt-bin bridge-utils virt-manager

add your own user to libvirtd group 

sudo adduser name libvirtd

run virt-manager GUI to create a new VM or import an existing image to it.

https://www.howtogeek.com/117635/how-to-install-kvm-and-create-virtual-machines-on-ubuntu/
